    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>FOREVER SHOWTIME</p>
        <p>The Checkered Life</p>
        <p>of Pistol Pete Maravich.</p>
        <p>By Phil Berger.</p>
        <p>Taylor, $23.95.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>FOREVER SHOWTIME</p>
        <p>The Checkered Life</p>
        <p>of Pistol Pete Maravich.</p>
        <p>By Phil Berger.</p>
        <p>Taylor, $23.95.</p>
        <p>Consumed with passion for the game of basketball, Press Maravich had one burning desire: to make his son Pete into the finest player the world had ever seen. The grueling drills and exercises that he invented worked wonders, and before he was even in high school Pistol Pete Maravich was an athlete with amazing skills, mastering behind-the-back passes, incredibly difficult shots and every aspect of ball movement. He would become famous for his flashy play, shaggy hair and floppy gray socks. In ''Forever Showtime,'' Phil Berger chronicles how this arsenal of abilities and individualistic flair took Maravich on a tumultuous journey from child prodigy to scoring legend at Louisiana State University to controversial National Basketball Association superstar, ending with his untimely death of heart failure in 1988 at the age of 40. Berger's prose is serviceable but often a bit clumsy. He overuses metaphors and can be excessively dramatic. However, ''Forever Showtime'' is worthwhile for fans who want to bask in the memory of Maravich's glory.</p>
        <p>Matt Polazzo</p>
      </block>
